[According to the Stop Polio Pakistan website, the 6 cases reported from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province are split between districts in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (3 cases) and districts in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Tribal Districts (3 cases) (see http://www.endpolio.com.pk/polioin-pakistan/polio-cases-in-provinces), with the most recent date of onset 9 Mar 2019 (see http://www.endpolio.com.pk/polioin-pakistan/polio-cases-district-wise-2019).

Reading the media reports in the remainder of this post, one can understand why Pakistan is significantly challenged in meeting the goal of polio eradication. (See my comments further down in this post.)

For the HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Pakistan, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6436992,140. - Mod.MPP]

******
[2] Pakistan (Khyber Pakhtunkhwa), violence
Date: Tue 23 Apr 2019
Source: Daily Journal [edited]
http://www.dailyjournal.net/2019/04/23/as-pakistan-polio-2/


Pakistani police say gunmen have killed a policeman assigned to escort polio workers during a 3-day nationwide campaign against the crippling disease.

Local police officer Wahid Noor says Tuesday's [23 Apr 2019] attack took place in the northwestern town of Bannu.

The incident took place a day after parents rushed hundreds of school children to hospitals in the northwestern city of Peshawar, claiming their children complained of nausea and vomiting after being given polio vaccinations.

According to Shaukat Yousafzai, a government spokesman in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province, their investigations show no student suffered illness because of a reaction to the vaccine.

He said panic gripped the province Monday [22 Apr 2019] when a rumor spread there that scores of children are not feeling well after taking polio drops. He said a man who initiated this rumor has been arrested.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

******
[3] Pakistan (Khyber Pakhtunkhwa), 2nd violence episode
Date: Wed 24 Apr 2019
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-polio/gunmen-in-pakistan-kill-policeman-guarding-polio-eradication-team-idUSKCN1S01CX


Gunmen in Pakistan shot and killed a police officer guarding a polio immunization team on Wednesday [24 Apr 2019], the latest attack on efforts to protect children from the crippling and sometimes deadly disease.

Polio workers are often targets in Pakistan, where hardline clerics and Islamist militants have claimed the government's polio eradication campaign is a foreign ploy to sterilize Muslim children or a cover for Western spies.

The police constable was on duty with a polio team in the remote Buner district in northern Pakistan when unknown gunmen opened fire, police chief Irshad Khan Yousafzai said.

"He was shot in the head and shoulder and died immediately," he said, adding that officers had been assigned to polio teams in the district after a rise in threats against workers.

Pakistan is one of the only 3 countries, along with Afghanistan and Nigeria, that suffers from endemic polio, a childhood virus that can cause paralysis or death.

The polio eradication campaign has had success with an intense program based around vaccinating vulnerable children. Only 4 polio cases have been reported since January [2019] [6 cases have been reported in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa since 1 Jan 2019, and one each were reported from Punjab and Sindh. - Mod.MPP].

However, suspicion of immunization drives threatens to undermine the government campaign.

A dozen people were arrested in northern Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province this week [week of Mon 22 Apr 2019], accused of organizing a campaign against polio vaccination and setting fire to public health facilities in the provincial capital Peshawar, the health minister said.

Hisham Inamullah Khan blamed "fake and malicious propaganda" for 44 000 children taken to provincial hospitals by parents fearing they had received bad polio vaccine, which, he said was "obviously was not true."

On Tuesday [23 Apr 2019], a polio worker was stabbed in the eastern city of Lahore after a heated argument with residents of an apartment building, police said.

That same day, a police officer was shot and killed by unknown assailants while on his way to join a polio team in the northwestern district of Bannu, police said.

[Byline: Jibran Ahmed]

