******
[4] Pakistan - fake news re: campaign
Date: Wed 24 Apr 2019
Source: Dawn [edited]
https://www.dawn.com/news/1478085


Anti-polio panic (editorial):
Pandemonium gripped KP amidst a province-wide polio eradication drive, threatening to stop this critical campaign in its tracks, which was ultimately the agenda of those who instigated the mass hysteria.

Thousands of children were rushed to hospitals by their panic-stricken parents on Monday [22 Apr 2019] after malicious rumours of adverse reactions to the oral polio vaccine [OPV] were disseminated over community and mosque loudspeakers, and via WhatsApp and other social media platforms, and picked up and reported, uncritically and without verification, by sections of the mainstream media.

The fake news was soon exposed as a total, willful fabrication in footage that soon emerged, but disinformation had already been spread, precisely because it fed into misconceptions about the OPV that have persisted despite the best efforts of public officials to dispel religious and medical concerns.

And though public officials scrambled to calm the public, holding a press conference within hours of the emergent crisis, by then, far too much damage had already been done.

In Mashokhel, where the rumour mill apparently originated, the local health unit was torched by rioters, and across the province, streets and hospitals were overwhelmed by a terrified public.

In the days ahead, there may be severe short- and long-term repercussions. Only yesterday [Tue 23 Apr 2019; see [2] above] [and today, Wed 24 Apr 2019; see [3] above], a police ASI assigned to a polio team was killed on his way to report for duty, and 2 new cases of the polio virus were detected in the province.

That a few malevolent individuals could hijack the vaccination drive, thus undermining the effort, dedication, and courage of polio workers, is proof of how tentative the gains have been in building public confidence in vaccinations.

There are already doubts about the extent of coverage this polio drive is able to achieve in the face of what has transpired.

The government must now examine measures to anticipate the possibility of fake news proliferating via social media, which can spread like wildfire in the absence of basic digital literacy among the masses.

The mainstream media, however, should have known better. For years, it has reported on the lives lost -- children who succumbed to the virus, and workers to the attacks of obscurantist elements -- and the disease burden on the country.

There must be a wholesale adoption of strict coverage protocols recognising the sensitivity, fragility, and security concerns of the anti-polio campaign. This is a dire setback, but it must not be allowed to derail the fight to eradicate this crippling, deadly disease once and for all.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Reading the media reports above is very disheartening, to say the least. It is beyond my comprehension how people can direct their political "activism" into anarchy that endangers the lives of innocent children. Creating fake news stories to scare people away from vaccination campaigns and directing violent acts on people involved in vaccination campaigns is more than I am able to understand. And this occurred in close temporal proximity to the senseless killing of a WHO consultant doctor working on the Ebola outbreak in Eastern Democratic Republic of the Congo. Another media report mentions the Taliban has not permitted the vaccination activities in parts of Afghanistan (see https://www.voanews.com/a/official-taliban-is-deprive-1m-afghan-children-of-polio-vaccine/4882669.html). What has happened to this world?
- Mod.MPP]
